    "shortDescription": "hear her ears here is a site-specific performance that we processed during our visit at Travers and the Glyptoteket museum. The starting point of our work was the local Danish language that we do not understand. We trans",
    "fullDescription": [
      "hear her ears here",
      "with Maarit Mustonen",
      "2018\nperformance\n1,5h",
      "{image 4}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn",
      "{image 3}\nPhoto: Rine Rodin",
      "{image 1}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn",
      "{image 8}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn",
      "hear her ears here is a site-specific performance that we processed during our visit at Travers and the Glyptoteket museum. The starting point of our work was the local Danish language that we do not understand. We transcribed the text for our performance through listening people speaking Danish in Glyptoteket on the 28th of November 2018 – we wrote down what we heard and how we heard it. hear her ears here was 1,5 hours long improvised performance that was based on repetition. The performance did not have a narrational beginning or an end. A viewer were welcomed to decide for how long you want to stay with the piece. ",
      "We were interested in the familiar yet strange quality of language, its physicality, and imaginative dimensions. We wanted to share our work hear her ears here in the Glyptoteket’s room number 10 because it hosts the sculpture of Demosthenes (384 - 322 BC), a Greek statesman and an orator. Demosthenes is considered as one of the most important public speakers in the Ancient Athens. According to a story, Demosthenes suffered from speaking problems in the beginning of his career. It is told that he practised by speaking with pebbles in his mouth and, to strengthen his voice, he spoke on the seashore over the roar of the waves. We found this fascinating.",
      "Supported by Frame Contemporary Finland and Forlaget Gestus"
    ],
    "contentHtml": "<b>hear her ears here</b><br />\r\n<br />\r\nwith Maarit Mustonen<br />\r\n<br />\r\n2018<br />\r\nperformance<br />\r\n1,5h<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/01.jpg\" width=\"670\" height=\"446\" width_o=\"2268\" height_o=\"1512\" src_o=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/01.jpg\" data-mid=\"74298996\" border=\"0\" align=\"left\" data-title=\"670 — 670 × 446\"data-hi-res=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/01.jpg\" /><br />\r\nPhoto: Marie Raffn<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/02.jpg\" width=\"670\" height=\"446\" width_o=\"1024\" height_o=\"683\" src_o=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/02.jpg\" data-mid=\"74246709\" border=\"0\" align=\"left\" data-title=\"670 — 670 × 446\"data-hi-res=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/02.jpg\" /><br />\r\nPhoto: Rine Rodin<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/03.jpg\" width=\"670\" height=\"449\" width_o=\"2268\" height_o=\"1523\" src_o=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/03.jpg\" data-mid=\"74232232\" border=\"0\" align=\"left\" data-title=\"670 — 670 × 449\"data-hi-res=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/03.jpg\" /><br />\r\nPhoto: Marie Raffn<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<img src=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/04.jpg\" width=\"670\" height=\"376\" width_o=\"5000\" height_o=\"2813\" src_o=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/04.jpg\" data-mid=\"77003656\" border=\"0\" align=\"left\" data-title=\"670 — 670 × 376\"data-hi-res=\"assets/projects/hear-her-ears-here/04.jpg\" /><br />\r\nPhoto: Marie Raffn<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<b><i>hear her ears here</i></b> is a site-specific performance that we processed during our visit at Travers and the Glyptoteket museum. The starting point of our work was the local Danish language that we do not understand. We transcribed the text for our performance through listening people speaking Danish in Glyptoteket on the 28th of November 2018 – we wrote down what we heard and how we heard it. <i>hear her ears here</i> was 1,5 hours long improvised performance that was based on repetition. The performance did not have a narrational beginning or an end. A viewer were welcomed to decide for how long you want to stay with the piece. <br />\r\n<br />\r\nWe were interested in the familiar yet strange quality of language, its physicality, and imaginative dimensions. We wanted to share our work <i>hear her ears here</i> in the Glyptoteket’s room number 10 because it hosts the sculpture of Demosthenes (384 - 322 BC), a Greek statesman and an orator. Demosthenes is considered as one of the most important public speakers in the Ancient Athens. According to a story, Demosthenes suffered from speaking problems in the beginning of his career. It is told that he practised by speaking with pebbles in his mouth and, to strengthen his voice, he spoke on the seashore over the roar of the waves. We found this fascinating.<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\n<br />\r\nSupported by Frame Contemporary Finland and Forlaget Gestus<br />\r\n",
    "contentText": "hear her ears here\n\nwith Maarit Mustonen\n\n2018\nperformance\n1,5h\n\n{image 4}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn\n\n{image 3}\nPhoto: Rine Rodin\n\n{image 1}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn\n\n{image 8}\nPhoto: Marie Raffn\n\nhear her ears here is a site-specific performance that we processed during our visit at Travers and the Glyptoteket museum. The starting point of our work was the local Danish language that we do not understand. We transcribed the text for our performance through listening people speaking Danish in Glyptoteket on the 28th of November 2018 – we wrote down what we heard and how we heard it. hear her ears here was 1,5 hours long improvised performance that was based on repetition. The performance did not have a narrational beginning or an end. A viewer were welcomed to decide for how long you want to stay with the piece. \n\nWe were interested in the familiar yet strange quality of language, its physicality, and imaginative dimensions. We wanted to share our work hear her ears here in the Glyptoteket’s room number 10 because it hosts the sculpture of Demosthenes (384 - 322 BC), a Greek statesman and an orator. Demosthenes is considered as one of the most important public speakers in the Ancient Athens. According to a story, Demosthenes suffered from speaking problems in the beginning of his career. It is told that he practised by speaking with pebbles in his mouth and, to strengthen his voice, he spoke on the seashore over the roar of the waves. We found this fascinating.\n\nSupported by Frame Contemporary Finland and Forlaget Gestus",
